	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>EU farmers find new fees for official inspections unacceptable  </h1>

			
			<h4>
												22 March 2014
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>On 21 February, Copa-Cogeca, the organisation for EU farmers and agri-cooperatives, expressed concerns over moves to impose fees on farmers and agri-cooperatives for the costs of official inspections under the new proposed EC food and feed regulation (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Topics/SPS-Food-safety/New-EU-food-and-feed-controls-to-include-full-cost-recovery" target="_blank">New EU food and feed controls to include full cost recovery</a>’, 7 July 2013).</p><p>Pekka Pesonen, Secretary-General of Copa-Cogeca, highlighted the increasing cost challenges facing European farmers as a result of higher input costs and higher production standards. He argued that recouping the costs of every inspection carried out on farms would be disproportionately expensive, and maintained that since “the additional cost of the fee cannot be passed down the food chain”, farmers will “have to bear the full brunt” of the increased fees. Describing the proposal as “unacceptable”, Mr Pesonen called on EU institutions “to ensure that these fees are not imposed on farmers and agri-cooperatives”.</p><p>However, Copa-Cogeca welcomed proposals to recognise “private assurance schemes which are already in place and certified by an independent body”, which it argued would help to “simplify the official controls, avoiding double checks”.</p><p>The aim of the EC’s May 2013 proposals&nbsp; is to ensure sufficient resources for effective official control systems and to address “known shortcomings of the existing system”. This will involve:</p>
<ul>

<li>the charging of mandatory fees “to all registered food and feed businesses… so as to spread the cost of controls across the entire chain”; </li>

<li>ensuring that future fees “enable the competent authorities to fully recover the costs incurred”, while rewarding business operators that consistently comply with reduced fee rates. </li>

</ul>
<p>It is recognised that increasing the range of mandatory fees and moves to full cost recovery could fall heavily on micro-enterprises and so, “as a rule, micro enterprises will be exempt from the payment of fees.”</p><p>According to an earlier evaluation of official control systems, it was estimated that EU member states collect between 20 and 80% of the costs of carrying out official controls. Given the economic and financial difficulties facing many EU member states, it was considered that this could potentially undermine essential control functions. It was estimated that extending the scope of mandatory fees and introducing full cost recovery could increase the funding for official control by between €2.3 billion and €37 billion per annum, depending on the basis on which fees are levied.&nbsp;</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>Copa-Cogeca, ‘Copa-Cogeca criticises MEPs vote to impose on farmers fees for inspection costs and to reduce the scope of official controls’, 21 February 2014</p><p>
<a href="http://www.copa-cogeca.be/Main.aspx?page=Archive" target="_self">http://www.copa-cogeca.be/Main.aspx?page=Archive</a></p><p>EC, ‘Communication to the Council and European Parliament: Healthier animals and plants and a safer agri-food chain – A modernised legal framework for a more competitive EU’, COM(2013) 264 final, 6 May 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://ec.europa.eu/dgs/health_consumer/pressroom/docs/communication-com-council-ep_en.pdf" target="_self">http://ec.europa.eu/dgs/health_consumer/pressroom/docs/communication-com...</a></p><p>EC, ‘Commission staff working document’, SWD(2013) 167 final, 6 May 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://eur-lex.europa.eu/LexUriServ/LexUriServ.do?uri=SWD:2013:0167:FIN:EN:PDF" target="_self">http://eur-lex.europa.eu/LexUriServ/LexUriServ.do?uri=SWD:2013:0167:FIN:...</a></p><p>EC, ‘Proposal for a regulation of the European Parliament and the Council…’, COM(2013) 265 final, 6 May 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://ec.europa.eu/dgs/health_consumer/pressroom/docs/proposal-regulation-ep-council_en.pdf" target="_self">http://ec.europa.eu/dgs/health_consumer/pressroom/docs/proposal-regulati...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Extensive lobbying is now under way to limit the scope of moves to full cost recovery for the extended range of mandatory official controls proposed by the EC in May 2013. Particular concerns arise over the financial implications of the EC proposals for those for whom it is extremely difficult to pass cost increases along the supply chain.</p><p>This raises important questions for ACP food and feed exporters – notably, who will carry the increased costs associated with increased mandatory controls and full cost recovery that are applied to imported products?</p><p>In the UK, where moves to full cost recovery were initiated in April 2012, the unit cost of fees charged for plant health inspections increased by nearly 250% between January 2011 and January 2014. This is only the tip of the iceberg, with the UK Plant Health and Seed Inspectorate implying that the number of inspections carried out on imports subject to reduced levels of controls (because of lower perceived risks) would need to increase fivefold in order to comply with required EU inspection levels.</p><p>Given the recognition that micro-enterprises could come under severe competitive pressures as a result of moves to full cost recovery and increased levels of mandatory controls, ACP governments may need to look to secure for small-scale ACP exporters exemptions from full cost recovery similar to those proposed for EU micro-enterprises.</p><p>ACP governments and private sector associations may also need to look for greater recognition of domestic, independently verified control measures, in order to avoid both double checks and double charges for necessary control measures.</p>
		</div>
		
